The client side of this issue is here:
https://github.com/spesmilo/electrum/issues/2149

Here is an example of the request sequence seen at the server:
```
INFO:ElectrumX:[15] processing {'params': [2], 'method': 'blockchain.block.get_chunk', 'id': 6676}
INFO:ElectrumX:[15] processing {'params': [1], 'method': 'blockchain.block.get_chunk', 'id': 6677}
INFO:ElectrumX:[15] processing {'params': [2], 'method': 'blockchain.block.get_chunk', 'id': 6678}
INFO:ElectrumX:[15] processing {'params': [1], 'method': 'blockchain.block.get_chunk', 'id': 6679}
INFO:ElectrumX:[15] processing {'params': [2], 'method': 'blockchain.block.get_chunk', 'id': 6680}
INFO:ElectrumX:[15] processing {'params': [1], 'method': 'blockchain.block.get_chunk', 'id': 6681}
INFO:ElectrumX:[15] processing {'params': [2], 'method': 'blockchain.block.get_chunk', 'id': 6682}
```
On the server side it should be possible to recognize a client requesting block 1 multiple times and consider this an "error" that will lead to disconnection.  As it is, clients can continue doing this forever, and though they are slowed by bandwidth limits, it still continues until the user realizes something is wrong and closes electrum.

Note that this doesn't happen on the "main" connection, as that is quickly disconnected due to incompatible address subscriptions.  It seems to happen only on "headers" connections that do not request data about specific addresses.

